 approaches for the future of public display projects, while also offering the reader curatorial tactics—what she calls queer curatorship—for exhibiting diverse sexualities in the twenty-first century. Tyburczy shows museums to be sites of culture-war theatrics, where dramatic civic struggles over how sex relates to public space, genealogies of taste and beauty, and performances of sexual identity are staged. Delving into the history of erotic artifacts, she analyzes how museums have historically approached the collection and display of the material culture of sex, which poses complex moral, political, and logistical dilemmas for the Western museum. Sex Museums unpacks the history of the museum and its intersections with the history of sexuality to argue that the Western museum context—from its inception to the present—marks a pivotal site in the construction of modern sexual subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aErotic artvExhibitions. 0aErotic artxExhibitions. 0aErotic artxMuseumszMexicozMexico City. 0aErotic artxMuseumszWestern countries. 0aSex in artvExhibitions. 0aSex in artxExhibitions. 0aSex in artxMuseumszMexicozMexico City. 0aSex in artxMuseumszWestern countries. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  asex, museums, display, exhibition, sexuality, normalcy, perversity, heterosexuality, homosexuality, intimacy, gender, race, history, archive, nonfiction, queer, curator, public space, taste, beauty, identity, performance, erotics, artifacts, material culture, sexual subjectivity, invisibility, visibility, discretion, affect, empire, soundscapes, architecture, phenomenology, touch, taboo, dissidence, david wojnarowicz, fire in my belly, virgen guadalupe con la cara de marilyn monroe, rolando rosa, censorship, resistance, gallery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv